Introduction¶

Hear, we will analyze data set from The Movie Database (TMDb). This data set contains information about movies 10865 released from 1960 to 2015.

Description of each column¶

  • Some of the names of the columns already describe itself, like ( budget in dollars, revenue in dollars, original_title, cast, homepage, director, runtime in minutes, genres, production_companies, release_date, release_year)
  • Another important column
    • imdb_id : IMDB System unique id
    • popularity: popularity score
    • homepage: website link of the movie
    • tagline: tagline of the movie
    • keywords: words used to give significant idea
    • overview: a general review of the movie
    • vote_count: votes given by viewers
    • vote_average: average votes given by viewers
    • budget_adj : budget in dollars,accounting for inflation
    • revenue_adj : revenue in dollars,accounting for inflation

Questions that I planned on exploring¶

  • Who the most casted star?
  • Which director has made the most movies?
  • What genre of movie are most popular?
  • Which year most of the movies released?
  • Who is the director that it's movie is the most profitable?
  • Which is the most profitable movie genre?
  • Which is the biggest budget movie genre?
  • What was the biggest Budget Movies each year?
  • What was the Movies that earned highest revenue each year?
  • What was high profitable Movies each year?
  • what is the relation between Movies Budget and Movies revenued?
  • who is the most famous directors?
  • who are the most famous Actors
  • Which production companies made the highest number of movies?
  • Which production companies earned the most?
  • Which genres are most profitable?
  • What is the month when most of the movies released?
  • what is the avrage Runtime movies?

what is the relation between Movies Budget and Movies revenued?¶

In [63]:
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
In [64]:
sb.regplot(df['budget_adj'].apply(log_trans),df['revenue_adj'].apply(log_trans), x_jitter=0.3,scatter_kws={'alpha':0.2})

Conclusions¶

  • Robert De Niro is cast in the highest number of movies
  • Woody Allen directed the highest number of movies
  • Steven Spielberg s the director that its movie is the most profitable
  • Drama is the most popular genre
  • 2014 is year when the highest number of movies released
  • Adventure is the most profitable movie genre
  • Action movies have the biggest budget of all movie genre
  • September is the months when most of the movies released
  • Jurassic World is the most popular movie
  • The Warrior's Way is the biggest Budget accounting for inflation Movies
  • Avatar is the biggest revenue accounting for inflation Movies
  • 53 movie out of 56 total is highest-grossing and in the same time the most profitable movies in each year
  • only 7 movies out of 56 total the biggest Budget and at the same time the most profitable Movies
  • Average Runtime of movies= 103 min
  • Warner Bros. is earned the highest profit
  • Universal Pictures made the highest number of movies
  • No strong correlation between Movies Budget and Movies revenues
  • From the introduced data, Vote average is normally distributed. The rest of the numerical data is skewed mostly to the left.
  • The number of releasing movies has increased over the years.
  • 1977 is the highest Profitable year, and 1966 is the lowest Profitable year
  • relationship of popularity & Gross Profit, show a strong correlation between popularity & Gross Profit.
  • From 1960 to 2015 gross profit has increased from 1.25 billion dollars to 17.5 billion dollars.
  • We can do additional research on Tagline & overview of movies to understand how movies emotion changes according to genres
  • Finally, the dataset that been given is containing a lot of missing values. Hence, I had to delete such rows after doing all the cleaning the data left was of 9772 rows; that means I lost a lot of data.
